sect2.para:
Who is an older adult? As life
            life
         expectancy has dramatically increased over the past century, and more adults experience healthier and longer lives, this basic question has taken on a special urgency. Aging, by definition
            definition
         , is a lifelong biological process, linked to socio-cultural referents and potentially accelerated or slowed by factors as varied as genetics and lifestyle (American Psychological Association, 
            2018
         ). Current social convention typically defines older adulthood as beginning around 60–65 years. Based upon this convention, older adults currently comprise 16% of the US population, or 54 million people, and with the aging of the baby boomer cohort, will comprise 22% of the population by 2040 (Administration on Aging, 
            2021
         ). Importantly, the older adult population reflects a heterogenous spectrum across functioning and health status, racial, ethnic, gender, sexual orientation, and cultural identities, geographical location, and financial/housing security. Of the current older adult population in the United States, 61% identify as White (US Census, 
            2020
         ) with projections for increasing racial and ethnic diversity, with the aging Latinx population to experience the most substantial growth (Federal Interagency Forum on Aging, 
            2020
         ). Furthermore, though exact estimates are difficult due to lack of consistently collected epidemiological data, by the year 2030, there will be approximately seven million older adult Americans who identify as LGBTQ+ (GLAAD, 
            2024
         ). Therefore, approaches to diagnostic interviewing with
            with
          older adults must integrate and center a lens of cultural responsiveness, cultural humility, and inclusive and affirming practices (Dixon et al., 
            2023
         ).

sect3.para:
Knowledge regarding
               regarding
             unique threats to safety is of paramount importance in clinical interviewing with older adults and includes careful assessment of (1) risk factors for suicide, (2) dementia-related self-neglect or risk of harming others, and (3) elder abuse. As older adults, and particularly older White men (age 75+) have the highest rate of death by suicide in the United States, routine evaluation is warranted (Mize et al., 
               2024
            ). Assessment of immediate risk factors, such as current suicidal ideation, intent, or plan, might begin with high-sensitivity queries (e. g., “Have you wished that you might fall asleep and not wake up?” or “Do you sometimes have thoughts that life is not worth living?”) and proceed to questions more specific to suicide (“Have you been thinking about how you might do this?”) drawn from measures such as the Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale (Mai et al.,
               2021
            ). Older adults are more likely to express serious intent
               intent
            and use lethal means (e. g., firearms), and rates are higher among isolated individuals, those in rural communities, and those with depression or substance use disorders (Mize et al.,
               2024
            ). Unique stressors affecting older adults that can put them at risk for suicidality include declining health, chronic pain, social isolation, thwarted belongingness, perceived burdensomeness, multiple bereavements, and involuntary retirement (Mize et al., 
               2024
            ).
